Hey! I took a look at that code snippet your colleague wrote. It's a pretty standard for loop to sum up all the elements in an array.

The loop is doing what it's supposed to do: iterating over each element in `arr` and adding it to a running total. One small thing you might want to mention is that `total` needs to be declared before the loop starts, otherwise it will throw an error. Here's how I'd suggest improving it:

```javascript
let total = 0;  // Initialize total before the loop
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  total = total + arr[i];
}
```

The logic is sound though! It's a straightforward approach to summing array elements. If you wanted to be more modern, you could suggest using `reduce()` which would keep the logic more concise:

```javascript
const total = arr.reduce((sum, current) => sum + current, 0);
```

But functionally, your colleague's code works fine - just needs that initialization step!
